hon 3 are subclasses of OSError, catching that single exception type should handle FileNotFoundError, PermissionError, IsADirectoryError, and other I/O errors. This is cleaner than catching multiple exception types or being overly broad with Exception.\n\n```python\ndef open_file(file_path):\n    '''\n    Check if the file opens successfully in the given path from the current directory.\n    \n    :param file_path: The path to the file to open.\n    :return: The file object if the file opens successfully, None otherwise.\n    '''\n    try:\n        return open(file_path, 'r')\n    except OSError:\n        return None\n```\n\nThis approach balances catching legitimate file access issues while avoiding catching programming errors like passing a non-string argument, which would be better caught during development. The function attempts to open the file in read mode and returns the file object on success, or None if an OSError is raised—this covers FileNotFoundError, PermissionError, and other file-related issues. I'll add this to candidate.py.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4710,"cache_read_input_tokens":24095,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4710},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"24c180eb-ca9d-4b11-a8d0-f3e1895cbb39","uuid":"0eeebbe3-5ec2-4ae8-abe0-ca751c61a891","request_id":"req_011CbdMXJqbY6a8ejsdiUvBj"}
